        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Solver (Ansys Mechanical 2022R2) holds current ISO 9001 certification; FDA CDRH-cleared solver version traceable to release notes. Internal DePuy Synthes FEA SOP v4.1 documents version control, input-deck review, and regression test suite."
      },
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022R2 is a commercially validated, ISO 9001-certified solver. DePuy Synthes SOP v4.1 mandates version-controlled input decks, peer review of model setup, and execution of a 12-case regression suite prior to each study. FDA reviewer independently confirmed solver version and SOP compliance. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds required Gradation 2 for a model risk level 3 / medium-influence COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-ncv",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical code verification acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Solver manufacturer verification test suite results (Ansys Mechanical Verification Manual, Release 2022R2) confirm correct implementation of linear and nonlinear solid elements used in the pedicle screw model. Patch test and cantilever beam benchmarks pass within 0.1% of analytical solution."
      },
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022R2 Verification Manual documents passing results for SOLID186 and CONTA174 elements used in this study. Patch test and cantilever benchmarks confirm correct stiffness matrix assembly. No custom user elements or subroutines were introduced, so manufacturer verification is sufficient for Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-de",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-de",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Mesh convergence study across three refinement levels (coarse ~180k, medium ~420k, fine ~890k elements). Grid Convergence Index (GCI) for stiffness QoI < 1.5%; Richardson extrapolation confirms monotonic convergence. Final mesh selected at medium refinement level where GCI < 2% for all three QoIs."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct. GCI values: stiffness 0.9%, yield force 1.3%, force-at-40mm 1.1%. All GCI values below the 2% threshold. Asymptotic range confirmed (GCI_fine/GCI_medium ≈ 1.02). Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level for a model risk level 3 COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-nse",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The pedicle screw compression-bending model employs a deterministic implicit static solver (Ansys Mechanical sparse direct solver) with a fixed, pre-converged load-step sequence. No iterative equation-solver tolerance sweeps are required beyond the default tight residual norm (force residual < 1×10⁻⁴ N). Because the solver produces a unique, reproducible solution at each load increment with no stochastic or iterative-tolerance-dependent variation, characterisation of numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor — separate from discretization error already assessed above — is not applicable to this study configuration. This is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Table 1 guidance that Numerical solver error need not be separately assessed when a direct (non-iterative) solver is employed and convergence is unconditional."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-ue",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error as defined in ASME V&V 40-2018 addresses variability arising from different analysts applying the same modeling tool to the same problem and obtaining divergent results due to undocumented degrees of freedom in model setup. In this study, a single, fully-scripted APDL input deck (version-controlled under DePuy Synthes SOP v4.1) was used across all three participating organisations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) with no analyst-selectable parameters. All geometry, material assignments, contact definitions, boundary conditions, and load application are hard-coded in the shared input deck. Inter-analyst variability is therefore structurally precluded, and the Use error factor is not applicable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-mf",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-mf",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Linear elastic titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) material model with isotropic hardening plasticity for post-yield behaviour. Contact modelled with augmented Lagrangian formulation. Model form justified by published material characterisation data and prior FDA validation studies on similar constructs."
      },
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa) sourced from ASTM F136 and confirmed by coupon tests reported in Nagaraja et al. (2022). Isotropic hardening plasticity captures post-yield softening observed in bench data. Augmented Lagrangian contact is appropriate for the screw-rod interface under compressive loading. Model form assessed at Gradation 3: physics assumptions documented, sensitivity to key assumptions (friction coefficient 0.1–0.3) evaluated, and comparison to bench data confirms adequate fidelity."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-mi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-mi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria",
        "description": "All geometric inputs derived from calibrated CMM measurements of production screws (tolerance ±0.005 mm). Material properties sourced from ASTM F136 and lot-specific coupon data. Uncertainty bounds on all inputs propagated through Latin Hypercube sampling (N=200) to confirm QoI sensitivity."
      },
      "rationale": "Geometric inputs (screw OD 7.5 mm, rod OD 5.5 mm, pedicle screw length 45 mm) confirmed by CMM measurement of three production units per the DePuy Synthes incoming inspection protocol. Material property uncertainty (E ± 3%, σ_y ± 5%) propagated via LHS (N=200); resulting QoI standard deviations are < 2% of nominal, confirming low input sensitivity. Achieved Gradation 3 meets required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-ts",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-ts",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples acceptance criteria",
        "description": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and DePuy Synthes R&D). All samples from the same production lot, verified by incoming inspection CMM and hardness testing."
      },
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs from a single production lot (lot no. DPS-7500-22A) were distributed across two laboratories (FDA: n=6; DePuy Synthes: n=5). CMM verification confirmed all screws within drawing tolerance. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.1%, consistent with expected measurement system variation. Sample size exceeds the ASME V&V 40 Gradation 2 threshold (N≥5) and approaches Gradation 3 (N≥10 with inter-lab replication), justifying achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-tc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-tc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria",
        "description": "ASTM F1717 static compression-bending protocol applied at a single crosshead displacement rate (5 mm/min) and ambient temperature (23 ± 2 °C). Single test condition only; rate and temperature sensitivity not explored."
      },
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 protocol condition (5 mm/min, 23 °C). Variation in crosshead rate (1–10 mm/min) and temperature (20–37 °C) were not explored, limiting the achieved level to Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 3. The shortfall is offset by the deterministic quasi-static nature of the FEA model (rate-independent plasticity) and published literature confirming that Ti-6Al-4V stiffness and yield force are insensitive to crosshead rate in the 1–10 mm/min range (coefficient of variation < 1.5%). See offset rationale in the decision record."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-eip",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-eip",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency of input parameters acceptance criteria",
        "description": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) mapped one-to-one to measured experimental parameters. Traceability matrix documents each FEA input parameter against its experimental measurement source and uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal input parameter traceability matrix (Appendix B of Nagaraja et al. 2022 supplementary material) maps each FEA parameter to the corresponding experimental measurement or specification. Geometry sourced from CMM data of the actual test specimens. Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon tests. Boundary conditions replicate the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry confirmed by fixture CMM. No assumed or literature-only inputs; all parameters directly measured. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds required Gradation 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-oc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-oc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison metric: E/uval < 1.96 (95% confidence interval) AND percentage difference < 10% for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Uncertainty validation metric computed per ASME V&V 20-2009."
      },
      "rationale": "E/uval values: stiffness 0.84, yield force 1.12, force-at-40mm 0.97 — all below 1.96 threshold. Percentage differences: stiffness 3.2%, yield force 4.7%, force-at-40mm 2.9% — all below 10% threshold. Both acceptance criteria met for all three QoIs across all 11 experimental constructs. Achieved Gradation 3 confirmed."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-rqi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-rqi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Relevance of QoI acceptance criteria",
        "description": "QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary performance endpoints specified in ASTM F1717 and directly referenced in the 510(k) predicate device performance summary. All three QoIs are mechanistically linked to clinical failure modes (fatigue crack initiation, screw fracture)."
      },
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three primary QoIs mandated by ASTM F1717 for pedicle screw construct evaluation. Each QoI is directly traceable to a clinical failure mode: stiffness to construct micromotion and pseudarthrosis risk; yield force and force at 40 mm to screw fracture risk. The QoIs are identical to those used in the 510(k) predicate comparison, confirming direct regulatory relevance. Achieved Gradation 3 meets required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-rva",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-rva",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Relevance of validation activities to COU acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation activity (ASTM F1717 bench test, N=11, two laboratories) directly replicates the intended COU geometry, loading mode, material, and scale. No geometric or loading surrogates used."
      },
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw production geometry, the identical ASTM F1717 loading fixture, and the identical load application protocol as the COU. Testing was performed at full scale with production-representative hardware (not prototypes). Two independent laboratories provide inter-laboratory reproducibility evidence. The validation activity is a direct, not analogical, representation of the COU, justifying Gradation 3."
